{"/service/ndnp/hihouml/batch_hihouml_cardinal_ver01/data/sn83025121/00294552303/1907121701/0175.xml":{"full_text":"Ml\nHAWAIIAN GAZETTE\nEntered at the Postoffice of Honolulu, H. T., Second-class Matter.\nSemi-Weekly Issued Tuesdays and Fridays.\nWALTER G. SMITH, Editor.\nSubscription Rates:\n\"Per Month .25 1 Per Month, Foreign\nJ3.00lPer Tear, Foreign\nTUESDAY\nS .35\n$4.00\nPayable Invariably in Advance.\nCHARLES S. CRANE. Manager.\nDECEMBER 17\nTRANSPORTATION PROBLEM IN AUSTRALIA.\nHawaii is not the only country that is wrestling with the transportation\nproblem, or that has wrestled with it recently. In the commonwealth of\nAustralia steamship communication with Great Britain has been a political\n-issue for several years and has at least once had its influence in putting one\nministry out and another one in. It was evidently a matter of very great\nsatisfaction to the present ministry of that commonwealth, when it was able\nto announce, last month, the completed negotiation of a contract with the\nOrient Steam Navigation Company for a fortnightly service between common.\nwealth ports and the United Kingdom under conditions as to speed and freights\nand accommodations which it believed would prove satisfactory to the public.\nAs this contract will have some effect at least on the activity of the com\nmonwealth in securing a line of mail steamers between Australian ports and\nPacific coast ports, it has a direct interest here, in addition to the interest it\nderives from the general subject to which it \"belongs. The contract provides\nfor a fortnightly service irom an approved port in the United Kingdom via\nBrindisi and Suez, calling at Colombo, Fremantle, Adelaide, Melbourne, Sydney,\nand Brisbane, and during the fruit season at Hobart, Tasmania, and returning\nbv the same route. The time from Brindisi to Adelaide is tobe 638 hours, a\nreduction of 5S hours in the present time, and going the other way the time is\nto be 650 hours a reduction of 46 hours on the voyage in that direction. The\nservice is to be with steamships of not less than.' 11,000 tons register, and\na speed of not less than 17 knots.\nThe speed and route of these steamships is dictated by the requirements\nof the mails. But the contract itself has a much more far-reaching purpose.\nThese steamships are all to be fitted -with refrigerating appliances of the most\njnodern and approved pattern, and there are very minute stipulations as to\nrates and regulations regarding perishable freight. A maximum rate of a half\npenny a pound for butter, and of sixty shillings a ton of forty cubic feet for\nfruit, is stipulated. Butter is to be carried in a chamber having a temperature\nof 35 degrees, and no fruit, cheese, or other odorous articles are to be carried\nin the same chamber with butter. Self-registering thermometers of an approved\npattern are to be used, and freight rates are to be the same to all commonwealth\nports. This last stipulation is a political rather than a business one, and is\nmade to put each state o'f the commonwealth on an equal footing, inasmuch\nas all are to contribute to the payment of the amount stipulated to be paid\nto the steamship company by the commonwealth. The ships are all to be\nprovided with wireless apparatus as soon as a shore station is provided by the\ncommonwealth government in Australia.\nWhile no rates for passenger service are stipulated in the contract there\nare stipulations for comfort and convenience ..for all .classes of passengers. The\ncompany is to withdraw from all steamship' trusts' or combination's. The contract\nis for ten years at 170,000 pounds Stirling ypar. Speedy and other\nrequirements are to be increased above those stipulated in the contract whenever\nany, competing line maintains a higher rate of speed or raises the standard\nof accommodations between Australia and' the United Kingdom. \"White labor\nonly is to be employed and there is to be no discrimination between union and\nlabor.\nThis contract may be regarded as exhibiting the latest developments in\nlong ocean transportation. It indicates what a highly developed commercial\nand agricultural people demand and what large transportation companies are\nwilling to give. It may well Te studied with some care by those who ard\nconsidering our own transportation problems.\n-H\nRECRUDESCENCE OF SWIPES.\nThe recrudescence of the swipe joint is a curious phase of the local liquor\nproblem. Perhaps, now that the police and the- License board have taken!\nibe burden of prosecuting violations of the liquor law off its hands, the Anti-Saloon\nLeague might devote some attention profitably to an explanation of\nthis phenomenon.\nOne doesn't have to be a kamaaina of very long standing to remember\nthe time when raiding swipe joints, picking up swipe drunks, and sending out\nthe wagon on hurry calls to quell swipe -riots, were among the very ordinary\ntut very frequent duties .of the police. Then came a' time when swipes ceased\nto figure in police annals. For the past five or six years the term has seldom\nbeen heard and then only in narration of a past time.\nThe usual explanation given is that five-cent beer has driven it out of\nthe market. Indeed, the local brewery has at times plumed itself on having\ndriven the demoralizing swipes into oblivion. The argument was made that\nwith pure, wholesome beer at five cents a glass, obtainable in the poorer sections\nof the town and cheaper by the can no one would go to the trouble of\nmaking swipes, in itself a dangerous occupation on account qf the vigilance\nof Uncle Sam's revenue department, or of drinking it when male when its\npurchase was a necessarily clandestine operation involving the liability, to the\nunpleasantness of being called as a witness.\nBut five-cent beer is still with us. In fact it is a complaint of some of\nthe saloonkeepers that the glass has grown so large that there is no\nroom left for profit. And yet at this very time swipes, with all its ugly\ntrain, makes its appearance again as an element in police administration. A\n4 'swipe joint\" of crude but abundant \"production was discovered by the police\na few months ago in Kakaako, and the proprietor is now serving a term in\nprison for it. The police yesterday, in raiding a crap game, discovered another\njoint, dedicated to the same kind of a Bacchus. And a third one was raided\nwith direct purpose. In each of these a half barrel of the stuff, ready for use,\nwas captured, and a barrel in process of, fermentation was found.\nWhat does it mean! Is it simply progress in the cycle of recurring taste\nwhich brings certain drinks, as certain styles of garments, into fashion again?\nla it a result of the License commission's policy of centralizing the saloon\nbusiness, leaving the residence districts, including Kakaako, Aala and Palama,\nto nnquenched thirst and native ingenuity, which has brought the swipe joint\ninto being again! Or, is it that the swipe joint has existed all the time, but\nthat a police administration which could not discover the existence of gambling\njoints was aiso near sighted regarding swipe joints where votes were involved!\nend that it is not a recrudescence of swipe joints but of police efficiency!\nA brochure or a monograph by John G. Woolley and John M. Martin,\ntreating the subject fully, ought to be of interest.\n\nSTILL THE GOLDEN STATE.\nIn its bulletin of progress for November 30 the California-Promotion Committee\ntells of great activity in the gold mining districts of the State. \"California\nhas given to the world, since gold was discovered in the State, a total\nof more than $1,500,000,000 worth of the metal, and indications are that there\nwill be greater development than ever with modern methods that are nowi\nbeing used in all the mining districts: During the month just past there has\nbeen increased inquiry into miping opportunities. In November, California\njjold mines produced over $1,500,000.\"\nThe same bulletin indicates a continuation of steam and electric railroad\nbuilding, crops harvested with better returns than were expected and a healthy\nimmigration. \"From\" returns made by railroads,\" the bulletin says, \"more\nthan 100,000 people .came to California on colonists' rates during the two\nreasons of 1907. Theseew settlers have been distributed all over the State\nand their coming has been of material help in the subdivision of large tracts\nof land.\"\nBuilding permits issued in San Francisco since the fire amount to\nin value of structures permitted, of which nearly two and a quarter millions\nfor November shows that the rebuilding pace is -being kept up.\nAn indication of' the weight of the blow dealt from Wall Street, however,\nis apparent in the item of bank clearings. Those for November were $122\n$232,23S,S72.09 for the corresponding month of last year,\nand $i75,162,7027 for November, 1905,\n1 .1\nWith the figure for bail aow quoted at $200,000 the banker who wants to I\nembezzle will have to do a wholesale business to make it pay.\nHAWAIIAN GAZETTEi TUESDAY, DECEMBER 17, 1907. SEMI-WEEKLY\nTHE PINKHAM-SAITO LETTERS.\nThe published letter of President Pinkham tp the Japanese Consul General,\nif correctly rendered back into' English by the Japanese translators, is nsT\nextraordinary official archive. \"We have no reason to doubt th\"e accuracy ia\nessential things, of the Jiyu Shimbun's rendering; as it accords with what we\nhave previously had from other sources; and it 'surely could have been no slight\nepistolary offence which drew from the forbearing Mr. Saito a response which\nhas been called by those who have seen it one of the most scathing communica\ntions to be found in the official correspondence of tho Territoriargovernment.\nThe facts leading tip to this strange affair have been described to us as\nfollows: \"When the '$10000 epidemic-occurred at Aiea, President Pinkham sent a\ncompetent white physician, Dr, Wayson, to look after the sick. Other aid being\nrequired the president asJseVf three Japanese doctors, Oyama, Mitamura and\nHaida, .to also;gd.,to\"Aiea, pujfting the matter to them as a public duty. These\npractitioners promptly went to work, making about forty trips to Aiea and\nmaintaining, at their own expense, a camp \"of isolation near this city. Dr.\nWayson made between twenty and twenty-five trips1 to Aiea, as many as were\nrequired of him, and served his patients' with the same painstaking care he\nwould have bestowed upon more profitablepatients. Neither he nor, tho Japanese\ndoctors expected pay.\nTime went on and the epidemic was cured at a cost, in shippers,' money, of\nten thousand dollars. The Japanese physicians went back to their private practice\nand said nothing about payj but' in a few weeks they were told that the\nPresident of the Board of Health, Mr. Pinkham, had sent a letter of thanks\nand an honorarium of $60 to Dr. Wayson. Naturally they thought they should\nhave recognition also. Hearing nothing from Mr. Pinkham they went to see\nhim, making polite inquiries as to his intentions towards them. They were ready\nto be satisfied with a letter of thanks, but Mr. Pinkham wanted Jto settle on, a\nmonetary basis and asked the Japanese doctors to make out a bill.\nForty trips to Aiea at .$10 apiece-came to $400 for each of the three doctors\nor $1200 in all. It was a snug sum but the bill could not be called high by white\nstandards. Even yet, the Japanese were ready to accept thanks and a fair\nhonorarium, but finding- they were to have neither for President Pinkham\nshowed no sign either of ready money or of epistolary gratitude the doctors\nlodged their claim with Consul General Saito. At this time, or about. then, the\nAiea plantation people got wind of 'the matter and through their agents, \"Wm.\nG. Irwin Co., Mr. Kichard Ivers acting, offered to pay the bill outright. But\nthe Japanese doctors declined the money of Irwin Co., their business being\nwith the Board of .Health. The question was up to Mr. Pinkham. He could\npay or he could thank; but the President of the Board of Health preferred to\nbulldoze.\nThe curtain here rises en the delivery of an official letter of President\nPinkham 's to the Consul .General of Japan. To say the least, it was a very\nquestionable letter. In form as published in Japanese and retranslated into Eng\nlish, it rebuked the foreign doctors for expecting to be treated on the same footing\nas citizen physicians; it denied their right to ask for a letter of thanks as well\nas payment; it told them that their countrymen are \"altogether too cocky\"\nand \"are considered a nuisance everywhere\" and observed that a Japanese\ndemand for the \"same \"rights and privileges\" might lead to serious trouble\nbetween the countries at interest.\nWhat had called out such a startling utterance) Merely a polite note\nfrom Mr. Saito asking due attention to an overdue account the bill of the\nthree Japanese doctors. Imagine the shock to so precise a man and careful an\nofficial as Mr. Saito over 'so insulting so \"racially\"vand politically insulting a\nreply. But he was equal to the need. Bis rejoinder is said to have been almost\nclassic; its language was calm and,' chaste and the self-respect of the writer\nlost nothing in either the, diction used or the statements made; but the result\nwas a prostrate and squirming Pinkham in the field of epistolary combat.\nThen Mr. Saito referred the letters td Governor Frear. At first, the executive\ndoubted that he had a place in the affair; but later, as we learn from Japanese\nsources, \"he wrote expressing regret Jot. the language Mr. Pinkham had used\nand he induced the latter to. apologize in. a letter which the President of the\nBoard is 'said to' have made'most complete and coupled with the request that it\nbe substituted, in the records of the \"Japanese consulate, for the letter that gave\noffense.\nWe are not officially advised as to the present status of the doctors' bill\nnor of President Pinkham: himself for reappointment. Regarding the bill,\nyesterday's Star says that it called for $1025, instead of $1200, and was finally\nsettled for $4 a visit.\nH-\nSUGAR LOOKS PROMISING.\nApart from the fall in cane Bugar,lireetly attributed to the financial panic,\nthere has been nothing in the market for three months to dull the anticipations\nof good prices tho coming year. As already shown in the Advertiser, European\nbeet sugar has ranged along a parity of eighty dollars a ton and more fori\nthat period. There has been no violent fluctuation, during that period, in the\ntransatlantic market. The fall -in the American market was stnted by New\nYork, authorities to- have been due to the closing of several refineries for lack\nof money. Within the past week a recovery of the raw sugar market has\nbegun, indicating that it is one of. jhe mpst buoyant things in the present commercial\nsituation. The .symptoms of its recovery follow so closely tho earlier\ntidings of the passing of the financial panic as to prove that the intrinsic state\nof the sugar market is just as strong as the. experts have been predicting for\nmonths it would be about this time.\nAccording to Willett Gray the statistical position of sugar is very good\nfor tie transition from one season to another. On November 27 there was a\nvisible supply, for Europe and America, of 1,726,783 tons, against 1,739,924 tons\nlast year, or a decrease of 13,141 tons. Estimates of the same date showed\nthe sugar crops of the world, including local consumption of home production\nwherever known, for 1906-07 to be 14,519,536 tons, against an estimate of\n14,234,000 tons for 1907-08, making an estimated decrease in the world's production\nfor the year now opening of 285,536 tons.\nUnder the date just mentioned Willett Gray stated that no stock belonging\nto importers remained in warehouse, and any local business must necessarily\nJje from one refinery to another. They said the situation in New York\nthen was quite abnormal, the circumstances being such as might have an important\ninfluence on the market a little afterward. As an instance it was\nstated that last season, when sugars were required to, finish out the year's\nmeltings, it was easy to bring them from the European markets, because Amer\nican and European markets were at a parity. This year there is a wide difference\nin this regard, the New York spot quotation, at the time stated, being\n30 cents per J00 pounds below the parity of European beet sugar. Naturally,\nit is observed, any needed supplies for the remainder of the year would come\nfrom the New Orleans market, where tfB degree test was quoted cents.\nWillett Gray were doubtful if the needed- supplies could be, brought from\nNew Orleans in time, owing to financial conditions combined with difficulties\nrespecting freight by. steamer from New Orleans north. They considered that\nthe required shipments, if made necessary in December and January, were well\nnigh impossible. It will have been seen, however, by a cablegram of Friday\nlast that, owing to a flurry in the New Orleans sugar market, the American\nSugar Refining Qompany had secured, on a low price, 40,000 tons of raw sugar.\nto the northern refineries.\nConcluding their review above quoted from, Willett Gray use these\ncheering words: \"There seems no doubt now that the acute stringency of the\nfinancial disturbance in the United States has been passed and improvement\nwill steadily follow, even if slow.\" The cabled rise in centrifugals last week\nindicates that the predicted improvement has set in speedily. There is a\npossibility that the big New Orleans purchase of the trust may have checked\nthe rise, yet such an effect in the conditions- existing can scarcely be more than\nbriefly temporary. It may indeed prove that the American's' large deal may\nproduce an advance, through compelling all competing refineries to hnstle for\nsupplies.\n\nv A CULPABLE PUBLICATION.\nThe most deplorable thing\" which has been printed lately, judging from its\neffect on tourists now in town and its inevitable effect abroad, is the Goodhue\nletter about the discovery, in tie system of the mosquito, of germs of an incurable\nmalady.\nThe presumption is that the infected mosquito is able such germs\nfrom one human being to another, from the sick to the well that is to say,\nsuch a presumption is raised in the minds of men who have given the subject\nno study.\nAbsolutely no preof exists that such transmission caa be made. If it could,\nthe superintendent, his assistants, the Catholic clergy and sisters at the Settlement\nand Dr. Goodhue himself would have been Inoculated long ago, for all of\nthem must have been bitten over and over again by mosquitoes which had\npreviously fed on the blood of the nhclean,\ntK.\nkSLiM\ncrews.'\nTHE BATTLESHIP FLEET.\ny\nThe battleship fleet has set sail oa its long voyage t the PaoMfc\nof a determined, if semewhat hytterieal, opposition t 'this movwaeat f\ntleis, on the part certain eastern newspapers- ami iiHram, tat apj to\nnow 6a its way. Whatever may have- been the, native of the Jffimttmmk\nhis naval advisers in, ordering this movement, or whatever aay be te4r vlttmt\nintentions regarding it, there can be no doubt that it is looked ea -by the-world\nas epochal in American naval affairs. On the surface of tfeiag H Jr.\nhard to see just why such deep importance should be attached tor it-, er intku\nit is hard to see why there should- be such hysterical oathsretfl.pawKagii.\njx. real jrapuriauce ux me luuveiueui, xj. uui mo inu infwwim kib\nrecognition of, tho place in world affairs which the Pacific and ksv Nftend m\nbeginning to' assume. The countries and peoples bordering the AttgBri rm\nGreat Britain, notwithstanding her world-wide empire have gives fthemebUea\n.over to a narrow provincialism which could imagine neither maritime\" pfrwer\nnor maritime needs outside of the Atlantic Therefore to send a fleet ef aay\ntfamg but third rate or obsolete types of war vessels, out of the Atkatie\nto them unimaginable. To such self-engrossed narrowness, the deter;\nof the President to give evidence in such a signal manner of his emaacipatMK\nfrom it, and of his statesmanlike vision of the trend .of events and the .direatiea,\nof world movements, was not only a shock but 11 reproach. NataraHy, it\ncreated resentment. Thosebound in the, chains of such narrowness eoaW Bet\nadmit that he had, been., .able to see things-in a better light or with-dearer\nvision than they1 j Henccs thofe must seek, some ulterior and sinister motive to\nJustify to themselves '\"their- own; narrowness.\nThis is especfaHy'tTnc of 'our own provincial brethren of the Atkati\ncoast. To some, degree lVJsdoubtlese true of foreign nations and peoples, aa4\nbesides they ar tgubtlejss influenced to some extent by the public, utterance-\nof the sentiment, justritlescribedj It is natural, therefore, that the departure e\nthe battleship fleVt '8houl,6fraft'ra'ct the widest attention.\nBut whatever the course \"of conclusions that brought- about this great aaval\nmovement, the fact that it is the first adequate recognition by any\nthe importance that is, and that shall be, of the Pacific, is sufficient to entitle\nit to all the attention, by cabinets and by powers, by communities and by-peoples,\nthat it is receiving,\nIt is an epochal naval, maneuver. It marks recognition or. the directiea\nof world events.\n-H-\nSpeaker Cannon's speech in accepting renominationas head of- the Hewe\nfrom the Republican caucus, printed in this issue, is a strong manifesto: It is.\nemphatic in its terse presentation of the Speaker's well-known concera'fer a,\npolicy of economy in national expenditures. Mr. Cannon is equally soiieiteas\nthat the Federal government should not assume financial burdens, testate\ngovernments and that the Federal authority should not trespass upoa th\nlegislative jurisdiction of the States. Tho Advertiser's Washington, correspondent\ncalls attention, in one of his letters received by last mail, to a.\npassage in Speaker Cannon's address whieh is interpreted as an attack oa the-President.\nThis is wbere, having said that \"we are not going to secure per\nfection in legislation and administration- in a day,\" he adds the observatieas\n\"Law is not alone in the matter it is the spirit of the people. In many so-called\nrepublics there is the shadow of constitutional authority without thee\nsubstance of either constitution or law.\"\n\nThe panic has had a stimulating effect on the Populists and they lava\ncalled a national convention to nominate candidates for president and vice president.\nIt will be an interesting sight when the old calamity-howlers come together\nagain from their exile in prosperity and declaim against the gold bngg.\nBut some figures will be missing. Sockless Jerry Simpson, if alive, is wearing\nsilk hose and could not .be admitted to the convention with them on, aad\nold man Peffer was so far denatured at last accounts that he owned his owa\nhome. Bloody Bridles-Waife. is out of the running and Tom Watson is a magazine\nplutocrat and, naturally, an object of abhorrence to his old friends.\nH\nFormer Officer Juen ia wrong in saying that Sheriff laukea was electtd by\nthe Democratic party. Tha.t party nominated him, bat the votes it cast were\nfar short of the number nee'ded to elect. laukea, like Trent, was elected bv th\ncombined votes of Democrats and independent Republicans. That the Democ\nracy had the good sense to put him on its ticket and support him solidlv i\na matter of congratulation, but the fact does not give it, or any factioa of it,\nthe right to control him in office or to compel him to govern his appointments or\ndismissals by political considerations.\nThe recent complaint of Vice President\nSchwerin, of the Pacific Mall\nsieamsnip Company, that American\nlines were, unable to meet the rates\nmade by the Japanese companies, because\nof the tatter's subsidies and the\nlower cost of\noperation, was told to\nConsul Paddock.\nWIDE FIELD FOR COMMERCE.\n\"I can understand that the American\nlines are handicapped,\" he said.\n..t4C .a ,IU uuudi mat the Japanese\ncompanies are able to\nquote lower\nWhen the Goodhue letter reached the Board of Healthy a considerable time rrates than American lines. As to\nago, it was put under seal, for the excellent reason that its. publication would\nhurt the tourist interests jof -Hawaii. Why was the seal broken? Why did the\nI Board of Health let loose so damaginga .missile.\nSAN FRANCISCO, November 29.\nThat Japan Is not. only planning to\noutdistance the United States In the\nstruggle for the commerce of the Pacific,\nbut has already driven the steamship\nlines of every other nation out\nof the Chinese trade was the Important\nstatement made yesterday by\nHenry L. Paddodk, TJnlted States Consul\nat Amoy, China, tvUo arrived In\nthis city on the PacIflSMall Steamship\nCompany's steamship Korea. Mr. Paddock\nwas accompanied by his wife,\n,-and after a few days stay In -San\nFrancisco will proceed to Washington.\n\"The Japanese'havtf captured the entire\nocean carrying trade of China\nfrom Hongkong to Shanghai,\" said\nPaddock yesterday. \"The British lines,\nwhich some years ago monopolized this\nbusiness, are doing nothing. The\nsame is true of the German lines. All\nnave succumbed to the competition of\nthe Japanese, aided by their large subsidies\nana the low pay of their\nrfl th'8 .CBUBtr uht grant\not uoHrse, 1 can not say. I\nhave not, made a study of that aspect\nof the question. But that the Japa\nIf the Pacific Mail ships go under tho British flag, those or American builil\nmight bo returned, on occasion, to their native registry. But as to the China,\na British vessel which registered as Hawaiian and came under the Air.ericaH\nflag with all other island vessels, her reclamation might be impossible. The\nchange of flags, as threatened, would bo a serious thing for Honolulu while it\nlasted, unless Congress should permit a foreign passenger and freight service\nbetween here and the Coast by exempting Hawaii from the inhibitions of the\ncoastwise shipping laws.\nThe promise of restitution mado to the \"Bulletin cirls\" will if f\nsilence the public criticism of tfce incidents revealed by Miss Dwight in her\nletter home, just as it has silenced the girls themselves about the Wcatherred!\nchapter of their story. Tho wonder is that a mere hint of a responsibility which\nau uuu uuuiiruoiy .assumed oy the manager, of the Bulletin ia Saa\nFrancisco had such a distressing effect upon the editor of the Bulletin he-e\nEvidently the latter thought there might be some way to crawl out\n\nPrince David and Prince Cupid are quoted in the Coast files as saying that\nPrince Salmon is a liar. The Tahitian comes back with his statement that the\nxionoiuiana are me same, it is fortunate for Tahiti that the Kaimaloa'is not\na position to sail.\nIB\nIt would be a graceful act for the Baseball League, having already\nbenefited lucratively from the visit of the Spalding players, to present -th\nvisitors with the whole of yesterday's, gate money.\nJAPANESE BOATS\n-CROWD ALL OTHERS\nnese are capturing the carrying trade,\nof the Pacific there1 is no doubt. The\nnew ships which they are putting ia\ncommission are of the most recent design,\nand unless some stimulus is gives\nto Americans to compete with them,\nwe may expec to see the Stars am!\nStripes become as unfamiliar oa the\nPacific as on the Atlantic\n\"That this should happen Is the more\nto be regretted because of the present\ngreat internal development of China,\nwhtch opens up a wide field for commerce.\nThere is no doubt that Chia.\nis now experiencing a wonderful regeneration.\nWhether this will be a\npermanent advancement, or Is simply\nli phase, the result of It- is\nthat China now affords a market which\nthis country can not negleit.\"\n1Y THE MOANrl\nSTMO II PORT\nxi.W5.en tiie S- s- osna arrived fre\nthe Colonies on- Wednesday last 'decking\nat half-past eight ia the\nao pweu aooaru that se\nwould sail for Victoria and Vaaeeaver\nat eleven o'clock that same Bight. Sir\ndid not sail, however, for twelve\nthat time and the reasoa was\na vigorous protest eatered by the\nIt is advertised by the\ncompany that\nby their boats will have a\nof seven hoars of daylight asfcere\nat Hoaolulu and. the passengers misted\non this. A\ncommittee of serea wa\nchosen to wait cm Captaia afermfcy\nand inform hia that unless hie' hWt\nwas held ia pert here for every\nthe seven hoars of cmyHgfct fetters\ncomplaining; aboat the MmUk\nseat to all the Amtmimi nan,\nThe eapMia promptly erewfed few ad\nthe -Moana did iot sail aatil\ngiving the pace ingots a mm\nto see-the eity of the beauties of wfcteh,\niney nau nearu.\n1\nIt","height":"29040","width":"20260"}}
